<div class="s2"><h1>Ludwig Shelters Under First Amendment</h1><p> <em>Virus Bulletin, June 1992, p.9</em><br/> <em>ISSN 0956-9979</em><br/> <em>June 1992</em></p><script type="text/rocketscript">var disqus_url = 'http://vxheaven.org/lib/axx01.html';</script>[<a style="" href="/lib/?lang=EN&amp;index=HI#axx01">Back to index</a>] [<a href="/lib/axx01.html#disqus_thread">Comments</a>]<br/><h2>Abstract</h2><p>Mark Ludwig, author of <em>The Little Black Book of Computer Viruses</em> (see <em>VB</em>, March 1992, pp 17-18) is pleading the <em>First Amendment</em> in order to justify the publication of the book. In a communication on <em>Compuserve</em> he stated `I have consulted with a lawyer regarding the legality of writing/publishing viruses, and have found that among the legal community, it seems unanimous that writing and publishing viruses, per se, is TOTALLY protected by the First Amendment.'</p><p>[<a href="/lib/axx01.html">Read the article</a>]</p></div>
